GSO projection and semi-c-theorem  
As we discussed before, when  is odd,
half of the states are projected out but the set of spectrum is not projected out. 
Only multiplicity of each R-charge is halfed.
Therefore if   is odd, the semi-c-theorem is compatible with
chiral GSO projection, namely,

Theorem    In type 0 string theory,  or the minimal twisted tachyon mass of
non-supersymmetric orbifold  in string
theory, increases under tachyon condensation.

What happen if  is even? In this case, some R-charges
are in fact projected out. Therefore the validity of the
semi-c-theorem depends on whether or not the minimal charge is
projected out by GSO projection. If it is not projected
out, then above theorem hold. We will get some idea from the details of examples given below.

Example 1. 11(1,3) theory with  condensation. 

To see the general feature of string spectrum, we study  the case where 
are relatively prime. We already tabulated all possible tachyon
condensation process of 11(1,3) theory in table . Here we give a
weight diagrams of mother and daughter theories where charges of  and  elements are put
together. For simplicity we give the diagram for just one process
11(1,3) ^(5,4)    5(1,1)4(1,1).
In this example, the final products after GSO projection are two separated 
supersymmetric orbifolds. All  elements are projected out while all  elements are
marginal. See figure . The second and third
diagrams in figure  is calculated by  and
 for  ring and by  and  for
 ring. The result is entirely consistent with the expectation
as  the diagram of 5(1,1) and 4(1,1) theories.

